liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: NASA has joined a number of scientific bodies which have found that July 2023 was the hottest month ever recorded. The US agency says that overall, July was 0.24°C warmer than any other July in its records, and "it's likely due to human activity". "Parts of South America, North Africa, North America, and the Antarctic Peninsula were especially hot, experiencing temperatures increases around 4 C above average," NASA says. "The record-breaking July continues a long-term trend of human-driven warming driven primarily by greenhouse gas emissions that has become evident over the past four decades. "According to NASA data, the five hottest Julys since 1880 have all happened in the past five years."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: NASA also says July was the hottest month ever recorded

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Residents of Hawaii are preparing two law suits against a major utility company Hawaiian Electric claiming it's responsible for the disaster which has so far killed at least 96 people. Our North America bureau chief, Jade Macmillan told News Breakfast residents allege that the company failed to shut off powerlines, despite warnings that strong winds could bring them down and spark fast moving fires. Here's what she told the show: Hawaiian Electric says that the cause of these fires still hasn't been determined, and that it will work with state and local officials as they investigate. But its share price has plummeted today amid these new questions in the aftermath of this tragedy. There is so much pain on Maui, but there's also growing frustration. People asking, for example, what caused these fires? People also still wondering — why residents in the worst affected areas weren't warned of the dangers sooner? Why the emergency sirens, for example, in particular areas, didn't go off? People also frustrated in some areas about the level of Government assistance that is being provided. They are reporting a really remarkable effort by locals, by volunteers who are doing whatever they can to help one another out. She reported specialist teams with cadavar dogs are still making their way through what is left of Lahaina and the death toll is still expected to rise.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Hawaii residents to sue electricity company over wildfire deaths

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Opposition Leader Peter Dutton and Shadow Sport Minister Anne Ruston have criticised Prime Minister Anthony Albanese's plan to talk with state and territory leaders about potentially giving Australians a day off if the Matildas win the Women's World Cup. In a joint statement, Dutton and Ruston say the Coalition will instead commit $250 million in funding over four years for community sporting infrastructure, if re-elected. "The prime minister's proposal of a one-off public holiday to celebrate the incredible success of the Matildas comes at a potential cost to the economy of $2 billion; not to mention sidelining the recent triumphs of other female teams in the Netball World Cup and the Ashes. It is a stunt which will have no legacy impact," they say. "The prime minister has tried to make the Matildas' success all about him. But we think there is a better way. We are opposed to Mr Albanese's public holiday and today we are announcing a policy that will instead make a lasting difference to the community and the lives of our young people. "This is a better and more lasting proposal than the Prime Minister's public holiday ego trip. It will mean better outcomes over the decades ahead for millions of young girls and boys across the country." Dutton and Ruston say the Liberal Party's investment wouldn't be contingent on state or territory government investment, but they would be encouraged "to match our investment to bring the total to $500 million". They say they are committed to the proposal, even if the Matildas don't win the World Cup.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: The Coalition says a proposed Matildas public holiday is a 'stunt' and 'ego trip' by the PM

props.alt: A bald man wearing glassed and a suit and tie stands in front of an Australian flag

"The prime minister's proposal of a one-off public holiday to celebrate the incredible success of the Matildas comes at a potential cost to the economy of $2 billion; not to mention sidelining the recent triumphs of other female teams in the Netball World Cup and the Ashes. "This is a better and more lasting proposal than the Prime Minister's public holiday ego trip. It will mean better outcomes over the decades ahead for millions of young girls and boys across the country."

Dutton and Ruston say the Liberal Party's investment wouldn't be contingent on state or territory government investment, but they would be encouraged "to match our investment to bring the total to $500 million".
They say they are committed to the proposal, even if the Matildas don't win the World Cup.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Having just discussed Australia's wine glut, we have results from the nation's biggest player, Treasury Wine Estates (TWE). It has reported a 3.3% decline in net profit after tax to $254.5 million on a 2.2% fall in sales revenue. However, its earnings before tax, interest and material one-offs climbed 11.4% to $583.5 million, with underlying net profit (excluding those one-offs) rising 16.6% to $376.1 million. The company says its strategy of "premiumisation" is working to improve profit margins on the wine it is selling, with its margin jumping 2.9 percentage points to 24.1%. It is targeting a margin of around 25%. TWE said demand for its luxury and premium wines remains solid, especially its flagship Penfolds brand, which saw both sales and profits rise more than 14%. The company says it expects demand for its luxury wines to continue being strong, while premium wine demand is expected to remain "consistent". However, "commercial" wine demand is expected to "remain challenged" with TWE predicting further volume decreases for the mass market segment. The company has declared a final dividend of 17 cents per share, which leaves the full-year payout for shareholders at 35 cents per share.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Treasury Wine Estates profits falls, but Penfolds softens the blow

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Good morning, welcome to the ABC Markets Blog. Wall Street closed higher, boosted by technology stocks as chipmaker Nvidia jumped on optimism about AI. The Nasdaq put on 1 per cent and the S & P500 rose 0.6 per cent. The Australian dollar fell to 64.55 US cents overnight because of fears China's largest private property developer Country Garden could default. Yesterday, the Australian share market hit a four-week low on worries about the problems in China's property industry. Companies reporting profit results today include vaccine maker CSL, jobs website Seek and Treasury Wine Estates. And the latest data on wages will be out, as well as the minutes from the Reserve Bank's board meeting earlier this month. Join us for all today's market's news.
